                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-154761 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-heart tag-parenting des-heart des-parenting news_keywords-heart news_keywords-parenting" id="post-154761">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Parenting and Heart Attacks</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Abby Sher			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-29T23:19:44+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 29, 2014 7:19 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 29, 2014 7:19 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;Anything I should know before I go home?&#x201D; I asked the chief cardiologist, trying not to sound terrified.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Just don&#x2019;t lift stuff over 10 pounds for a few weeks.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;My baby is over 10 pounds.&#x201D;<span id="more-154761"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/30/opinion/1030PRIVATELIVES/1030PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject"
                                            role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/30/opinion/1030PRIVATELIVES/1030PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/30/opinion/1030PRIVATELIVES/1030PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg"
                                                    id="100000003205075" width="480" height="618" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="618">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sara Drake</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He shrugged. &#x201C;Do what you can.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I was 40 years old and had just given birth to my third child when, three months later, I had a heart attack. I had low cholesterol and blood pressure, and no family history of heart disease. I was training for a half-marathon.
                                        While they were stenting one of my coronary arteries, five different physicians asked me if I&#x2019;d done cocaine. I told them the raciest I got was kombucha.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Two days later, I was untethered from the beeping machines and set free. Walking timidly toward the car with my husband, Jay, I wanted to feel overjoyed. To run into our Brooklyn apartment, throw my children in the
                                        air and cry &#x201C;I&#x2019;m alive!&#x201D; But honestly, I couldn&#x2019;t imagine how I&#x2019;d take care of myself, let alone them. Every twinge in my chest made me catch my breath and check my pulse. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Helloooo?&#x201D; I called out softly as I opened the door.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My 3-year-old son yelled, &#x201C;Mama!&#x201D; He proudly showed me the newest scrape on his elbow and said he had had ice cream twice. My 5-year-old daughter barely glanced up from the kitchen table. When I kissed
                                        her head, she said I could help her paint her new jewelry box if I was neat. The baby was in my mother-in-law&#x2019;s arms, blinking at me curiously from behind his new bottle. My breasts immediately started leaking
                                        when I saw him. Since I was now on blood thinners, and one theory for the heart attack was a hormonal imbalance, the doctors had insisted I wean. I smelled like sweat and sour milk. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We talked to the kids at dinner about why, instead of picking them up from school as promised, I had to go to the hospital and stay for two days. We used calm, vague words about one of my veins needing to open up more.
                                        How I was all better now, but would have to do things a little more slowly for a while.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That first night home, I asked Jay to read the bedtime stories. I didn&#x2019;t know how to lie on the kids&#x2019; beds without feeling pressure on my rib cage. I also convinced myself that I was too short of breath
                                        to read. If I was having another heart attack, I really didn&#x2019;t want it to happen in the middle of &#x201C;Corduroy.&#x201D; </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After the kids fell asleep, Jay made me sit next to him on the couch and watch some mindless TV. The doctors were confident the heart attack was a fluke. I had no parting instructions besides no lifting. One of the
                                        cardiologists said he wanted to see me at the marathon finish line. Still, I stared at the TV hungrily for hours, wishing I could see my heart rate squiggle on the screen, assuring me I was really here.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We made it through the night. Then we made it through a whole day. And another. I regained my energy, but the kids sensed that something was different about me. I was walking more slowly, and I didn&#x2019;t give piggyback
                                        rides or join in tickle parties.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My son coped by turning into a lion. Instead of talking, a lot of times he gnashed his teeth and roared at me. Then he said his imaginary friend Marcel was home from school for two days because &#x201C;her heart has
                                        an extra beat.&#x201D; I made him repeat that for Jay. We&#x2019;d never used the words &#x201C;heart&#x201D; or &#x201C;attack&#x201D; in front of the kids. Apparently, we didn&#x2019;t need to. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My daughter, who had seemed so casual and unaffected when I came home, was especially inconsolable. She was scared of the dark, the light, the word &#x201C;dead&#x201D; if she heard it in passing. When I went out one
                                        night with a friend, my daughter howled at our sitter, &#x201C;You just want my mom to die!&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I recognized her terror. I&#x2019;d lost my dad when I was 11 to a swift cancer. One day we were sharing orange sherbet and a few weeks later I was staring at his coffin. I was so confused and angry that he&#x2019;d
                                        abandoned me just before back-to-school haircut day. Everything about his illness and death felt like a bad secret. The quick snap of his hospital bedsheets as he tried to hide his IV. The barricades I made so he
                                        couldn&#x2019;t come into my room while I was scribbling in my diary. I spent a lot of time making sure he never saw me cry. Like, if we didn&#x2019;t talk about it, the cancer would disappear instead of him.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now I saw the same silent caginess in my daughter. Slamming doors and chewing her fingernails. Sizing me up as if I were highly unreliable. I spent a lot of time avoiding eye contact with her and fighting about her
                                        nail biting. (Maybe if I make her miserable she won&#x2019;t be devastated if I die?) When it was time for good-night kisses and hugs, I was quick and wimpy, barely letting our chests touch. As if I could save both
                                        of our hearts from breaking. I didn&#x2019;t know how to convince her or myself that I was here to stay. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My baby is the only one who really trusted we&#x2019;d all be fine. He came with me to most of the follow-up appointments, giving wide gummy smiles and charming all the doctors and nurses. We got passed around between
                                        specialists. Everyone was kind but a little confused by what had happened. Until we met a cardiologist named Jose Meller. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He sat on the edge of his desk because there were too many accordion folders piled up on his chair, and asked me random questions &#x2014; Are you flat-footed? Double-jointed? Can you curl your tongue? &#x2014; jotting
                                        down all my answers in longhand. His diagnosis: fibromuscular dysplasia, which is a relatively rare arterial disease that is often nonprogressive and nonthreatening, but can sometimes manifest in artery dissection,
                                        or tears. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Does this mean her other arteries can dissect?&#x201D; asked Jay. (Answer: Not likely).</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Do I have to stop running?&#x201D; I pounced. (No.) &#x201C;What about coffee?&#x201D; (Enjoy.)</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Should we put it on the family history form for kindergarten?&#x201D; Jay added. (Not necessary.)</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dr. Meller waited for us to run out of questions. He and the baby continued to make eyes at each other &#x2014; like, look at these two crazies. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;You are fine, Abigail. I&#x2019;ll see you in a year just to take more pictures but it will all be the same. Do you want to know what you do now?&#x201D; Dr. Meller asked. He stuck his tongue out and got a baby
                                        giggle of agreement. &#x201C;You go home and enjoy your family. You go back to life.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That was harder than he made it sound. I swallowed my Plavix and aspirin every night. I bought a fancy heart rate monitor for running. I did yoga and meditated. But the most difficult part of recovery was reconnecting
                                        with my kids.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One night, a few weeks after Dr. Meller&#x2019;s edict, we were doing our bedtime routine and my daughter asked me to lie down with her. Usually I made up a hundred excuses why I couldn&#x2019;t. This time, I took a
                                        deep breath and climbed in between her dollies. I stroked her head and sang her the lullaby I&#x2019;d made up when she was in my womb. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Sonya Joan, Sonya Joan, you&#x2019;re my favorite person</em></p><em>
</em>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>And I love you, yes I love you, for always</em></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then I heard a sniffle. And a sob. I stopped singing.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;What is it, sweetie?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She whimpered some more before answering. &#x201C;You said you love me for always, but what if&#x2026;?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I held her tight. It was all I could do. </p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//abbysher.com/ ">Abby Sher</a> is the author of &#x201C;Amen, Amen, Amen: Memoir of a Girl Who Couldn&#x2019;t Stop Praying.&#x201D;</em></p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
